    Functional Interface:
    This is a functional interface and can therefore be used as the assignment target for a lambda expression or method reference.
    @FunctionalInterface
public interface Transceiver
extends NamedObject
    Functionality that is common to Broadcasters, Listeners, Repeaters and potentially other classes that are involved in handling messages. The isOn() method returns true if the transceiver is enabled. When enabled, the handle(Transmittable) method calls onHandle(Transmittable) to allow the subclass to handle the message.

    Convenience Methods

    The following convenience methods call handle(Transmittable) with the appropriate class of message.

    • trace*() - The listener handles a Trace message
    • information*() - The listener handles an Information message
    • narrate() - The listener handles a Narration message
    • warning*() - The listener handles a Warning message
    • quibble*() - The listener handles a Quibble message
    • problem*() - The listener handles a Problem message
    • halt*() - The listener handles an OperationHalted message

    Debugging

    A Transceiver provides access to a Debug object which has the class context (also CodeContext) provided by the method debugClassContext().

    The isDebugOn() provides convenient access to Debug.isDebugOn() and the ifDebug(Runnable) executes the given code if debugging is on. Several convenience methods also provide tracing which originates Trace messages only if debugging is on.

    Because Broadcasters, Listeners and Repeaters are debug transceivers, they inherit all the methods in this class. This means that a subclass of BaseRepeater can simply call a trace() or quibble() method and it will automatically be gated by the functionality of Debug. This makes it especially easy to declare and control debug tracing. In the example below, the trace() statement can be enabled by running the application with -DKIVAKIT_DEBUG=EmployeeLoader. See @Debug for more details on the KIVAKIT_DEBUG syntax.

    Debug Tracing Example 

     class EmployeeLoader extends BaseRepeater
 {

     [...]

     trace("Loaded $ employees", employees.size());

 }
    * @author jonathanl (shibo)
